In TypeScript, you can use the `as` keyword to assert that a value has a specific type, even if the type checker doesn't know for sure. For example:
```
let value: string | number = 'foo';
console.log(value.asNumber()); // Type error, value is a string
console.log(value.asString()); // OK, value is a string
```
Alternatively, you can use the `infer` keyword in a type guard to extract the specific type from an union type and give it a new name. For example:
```
type MyUnion = string | number;
type MyType = MyUnion & { foo: string };

function assertMyType<T extends MyUnion>(value: T): asserts T is MyType {
  throw new Error('assertMyType: bad type');
}

let value: MyUnion = 'foo';
assertMyType(value);
```
This will give you a compile-time error if value is not of type `MyType`, even though it is a subtype of `MyUnion`.

